  <!-- FAQ -->
  <div id="faq" class="mb-6">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-3">
      <details class="border-l-4 border-gold/40 bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
        <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          What external factors affect disc stack centrifuge performance?
          <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
          The 8 main external factors are: (1) feed temperature — lower temps increase viscosity and reduce efficiency, (2) feed tank agitation — settled feed creates sludge spikes that disrupt operation, (3) feed pump selection — incorrect type causes pulsation or cavitation, (4) pre-filtration — oversized particles contaminate the centrate, (5) discharge piping back-pressure, (6) sludge ejection cycle timing, (7) operating water quality and pressure, (8) ambient temperature affecting gearbox oil viscosity and feed properties.
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="border-l-4 border-gold/40 bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
        <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          How does feed temperature affect centrifuge separation performance?
          <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Feed temperature determines the viscosity of the liquid being separated. Lower viscosity (higher temperature) allows centrifugal force to move particles more rapidly. For every 10°C reduction in temperature, viscosity typically increases 10–20%, reducing separation efficiency proportionally. Heavy oils must be heated to 180–200°F. Even water-based coolants benefit from operating above 70°F for optimal sub-micron particle removal.
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="border-l-4 border-gold/40 bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
        <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          Why does feed tank agitation matter for centrifuge performance?
          <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Without agitation, sludge settles to the bottom and the centrifuge receives alternating clean liquid (from the top) and highly concentrated sludge (from the bottom). These concentration spikes overload the bowl's sludge space causing premature filling, liquid seal instability, and inconsistent centrate quality. A properly sized agitator keeps sludge uniformly suspended throughout operation.
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="border-l-4 border-gold/40 bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
        <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          What back-pressure is acceptable on a disc centrifuge centrate outlet?
          <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Acceptable centrate back-pressure is typically 0–15 PSIG on the light phase outlet and 0–10 PSIG on the heavy phase outlet. Excessive back-pressure compresses the liquid seal ring and can cause seal break. Back-pressure is created by long or undersized centrate piping, elevation changes, flow control valves, and downstream equipment resistance.
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="border-l-4 border-gold/40 bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
        <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          Why should the sludge tank under a disc centrifuge be vented?
          <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
          During sludge ejection, the high centrifugal force creates a pressure pulse with the discharged sludge. A sealed sludge tank traps this pressure and causes ejected sludge to deflect back into the centrifuge bowl, interfering with the bowl opening mechanism. In worst-case scenarios, pressure buildup can rupture the tank, causing equipment damage or operator injury. Always vent the sludge tank to atmosphere.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>

